==English==

===Etymology===
{{etyl|enm|en}} ''[[lynspin]]'', compound of ''[[lins]]'' 'axletree' and ''[[pin]]'', from {{etyl|ang|en}} ''[[lynis]]'' 'linchpin', from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} *''luniso'' (compare {{etyl|de|-}} {{term|Lünse|lang=de}}), from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} (compare {{etyl|cy|-}} {{term|olwyn||wheel|lang=cy}}, {{etyl|xcl|-}} {{term|ողն||back; spine, backbone|lang=xcl}}, {{etyl|sa|-}} {{term|tr=āṇís|lang=sa}}). Figurative use attested from the mid-20th century.

===Alternative forms===
* [[lynchpin]]

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# a pin inserted through holes at the end of an axle, so as to secure a wheel
# {{context|figuratively|lang=en}} a central [[cohesive]] source of [[stability]] and [[security]]; a person or thing that is critical to a system or organisation.

